    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_18333722" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/18333722" />
    <a title="Werner" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/903390-werner"><img alt="Werner" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1216337931p2/903390.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/18333722?book_show_action=true">Mar 21, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Werner" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Werner" href="/user/show/903390-werner">Werner</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Fans of serious science fiction</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Werner by: </span>
      It was required reading for a course I took on science fiction
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/903390-werner?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer18333722" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6881271232964514128">Following the destruction of 20th-century civilization in a nuclear war, Jewish nuclear scientist Edward Isaac Leibowitz converted to Catholicism and founded a monastic order charged with salvaging the books that record humanity&apos;s heritage of literature and knowledge. Though the novel opens centuries after his death, his influence lingers throughout it, as the Order of Leibowitz fulfills its mission (like their monastic predecessors after the fall of the Roman Empire) to preserve written culture</span>
  <span id="freeText6881271232964514128" style="display:none">Following the destruction of 20th-century civilization in a nuclear war, Jewish nuclear scientist Edward Isaac Leibowitz converted to Catholicism and founded a monastic order charged with salvaging the books that record humanity's heritage of literature and knowledge. Though the novel opens centuries after his death, his influence lingers throughout it, as the Order of Leibowitz fulfills its mission (like their monastic predecessors after the fall of the Roman Empire) to preserve written culture in the midst of a new Dark Ages, through the dawn of a new Renaissance, to the rise of another high-tech, spacefaring, nuclear-capable civilization. The hope behind all of their efforts is that this recorded knowledge (which is not evil in itself) can ultimately be used to serve a healthy human community living in accordance with God's design. But at the book's end, hubris-drenched human nature has forgotten nothing and learned nothing, setting the stage for a powerful ending.<br /><br />Published in the midst of the Cold War, this book received considerable acclaim from the academic/critical community, who recognized it as bearing a strong message against nuclear war. It obviously does; but any serious reading of the book makes it clear that this is simply one part of a broader pro-life message (it also strongly condemns euthanasia), and that this in turn grows out of a broader, basic Christian message rooted in Miller's committed Catholic faith: that human life should be lived in communion with God and other people who bear God's image, and that the uses of knowledge should be to foster life in this kind of communion, not the aggrandizement of some human beings at the expense of others. But though it is a serious novel of ideas, it doesn't lack for character, plot, and vivid world-building, and it never becomes boring or preachy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6881271232964514128" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

